After looking at scenery design proposals for FGFS, I decided to express
my opinion on the subject.


In the discussions about bits and bytes we should not forget one of the
most important features of FGFS (maybe the most important one) -
compatibility.

The compatibility of scenery data is needed between different platforms,
between different versions of FG (upwards/downwards) and between
sceneries produced by different scenery design tools. By different
platforms I also mean different FG implementations for one hardware
platform. We can even view MSFS as one of the platforms.

We need to develop a file format for DISTRIBUTING and STORING sceneries
that would ensure every scenery can be used with every implementation of
FG. In particular, it should meet following criteria:

Upward compatibility. The scenery data should be usable on all future FG
versions. Where possible, the scenery should gain new features and
functionality added to future versions of FG.

Downward compatibility. The scenery data should be usable on all
previous versions of FG. Where necessary, the scenery should lose
features and functionality not available in these versions.

Compatibility across platforms. The scenery data should be usable on all
platforms supporting FG. Where possible, the scenery should gain new
features and functionality available on the target platform. Where
needed, it should be stripped down.

Extensibility. We cannot predict today, which scenery features will be
desired in the future. The scenery file format should be open to
extensions.

Decentralism. Developers of different FG implementations and scenery
design tools should have as much freedom as possible when determining
relevant file formats.


IMHO, it is impossible to develop a single scenery file format that
would meet these criteria. The solution could be to use different file
formats for distributing sceneries and for storing scenery data actually
accessed by FG. Conversions between these formats should be done by
automatic converters.

Different 'levels' of scenery file formats would be needed. The lowest
level would be scenery data actually accessed during the flight. This
format would be highly optimized for the target platform and the
implementation of FG. Here, "tricks" like splitting the world into flat
regions should be used. This format does not need to be compatible with
other FG versions or platforms, so there is a great freedom for
optimizations. Sceneries should NEVER be designed in this format.

The next level ("Mid-Level") would be some file format understood by all
FG implementations. This compatibility, however, should not act as a
restricting factor for it's features. For this reason, different (not
necessarily compatible) versions of this file format can be defined.
Sceneries should NEVER be designed in this format.

There should be some minimal mid-level format understood by all FG
implementations. Each implementation MUST provide a converter from the
minimal format into it's low-level format and MAY also provide
additional converters from more sophisticated mid-level formats.

The next level ("High-Level") would be file formats produced by scenery
design tools and actually used to distribute sceneries. Each scenery
design tool MUST provide a converter for converting it's scenery files
into the minimal mid-level format and MAY also provide additional
converters for more sophisticated mid-level formats.

These rules ensure that ANY high-level scenery file format can be
converted into ANY low-level format.


As an illustration, let's consider a following scenario. We have some
scenery design tool ("PEAK") that produces mountains and the first
version of FG ("FG1") that can display only plain polygons. We design a
mountain "covered with a forest".

PEAK supports only the minimal mid-level scenery file format ("SF1"),
which only allows defining plain polygons. PEAK includes a converter
("PEAK2SF1") that converts out scenery into SF1. FG1 includes a
converter ("SF1TOFG1") that finally converts the SF1 file into the
low-level format used by FG1. We get a plain green mountain.

Later, a Mac version of FG1 ("FG1MAC") is released, which uses a
different low-level format due to a different byte order. However, it
includes it's own converter which converts the SF1 file into it's
low-level format.

Later, a second version of FG ("FG2") is released, which now allows
texture-mapped polygons. It defines a new mid-level scenery file format
("SF2") that allows defining textured polygons. However, it still
contains (it MUST - see the rules) a converter from SF1 ("SF1TOFG2"),
which converts our SF1 file into it's low-level format. However, the
mountain appears non-textured, because SF1 does not support textures and
a converter from PEAK into SF2 is not available yet.

Later, a new version of PEAK is released that supports textures. It also
includes a second converter ("PEAK2SF2") which can convert files into
SF2. The user of our scenery downloads PEAK 2 and uses PEAK2SF2 to get a
file in SF2. Then, he uses the converter supplied with FG2 to convert
SF2 into the low-level format. Now he has a textured mountain, although
the original author of the scenery never thought of such a possibility.

Later, an SGI version of FG ("FGS") is released, which supports fractal
trees. It defines another mid-level scenery file format ("SF3") that
supports fractals. However, it includes low-level converters only from
SF1 (required) and SF3. Because PEAK does not support SF3 at this time,
the user has no other choice but to convert it into SF1 and get a plain
non-textured mountain. The scenery lost one of it's features (texture)
because it was necessary.

Later, a 3rd version of PEAK is released, which includes a converter to
SF3. The user of our scenery downloads PEAK 3, uses PEAK2SF3 to get
fractal trees in the mid-level scenery and uses the converter supplied
with FGS ("SF3TOFGS") to convert it into low-level. He sees a beautiful
mountain covered with fractal trees and decides to design some mountain
scenery himself.

Although designed on and for an SGI, his scenery is compatible to all
versions of FG. For example, a user of FG1 can use a "PEAK2SF1"
converter (which MUST exist - see the rules) and then "SF1TOFG1". Of
course, the mountain will look much worse than it was on an SGI, but it
will still be there.

Later, some FS5 fanatic decides to make FS5 FG-compatible. He writes
converters from SF1 (he MUST do it) and SF2 into the BGL file format.
Now all FG scenery can also run on FS5.

Later, he buys himself an SGI workstation and throws his FS5 away.
However, he misses some great ScBuilt scenery of his home state. So he
writes converters from BGL into SF1 (he MUST do it) and into SF2.

Now it is possible to use all FS5 sceneries with FG and all FG sceneries
with FS5. Note that here FS5 is treated both as a design tool (where BGL
files come from) and as a target platform (where BGL files run on).

Also, sceneries gained or lost some features depending from the actual
FG implementation without _any_ action from scenery authors.

...Now let's go back into the real world


The low-level format should be determined only by programmers of an
actual implementation of FG. It's main purpose is to store scenery data
in a way that could be accessed by the FG implementation in a very
effecient way.

The mid-level format can theoretically be defined by everyone. However,
because a new mid-level format only makes sense if a (in future) large
number of converters is developed, much cooperation and careful thinking
is required here in order to reduce the needed amount of efforts.

For a minimum mid-level format, I would suggest a set of polygons having
solid colors and defined using _real-world_ coordinates. No hidden
surface removal or optimization allowed here - it will be done by a
converter into the low-level format and will highly depend from the
actual hardware used.

The main purpose of the mid-level file format is to allow independent
development of scenery design tools and FG implementations by splitting
the conversion process into two non-overlapping parts.

The high-level format should be determined only by the author of the
corresponding scenery design tool. It's main purpose is to store
sceneries that would automatically enhance themselves with new versions
of FG or scenery design tools. Such enhancements would be made possible
by new coverters supplied with FG or these tools.


Mid-level and high-level formats should be as compatible across
different platforms as possible. I think plain ASCII text files should
be used here. Also, we shouldn't put any artifical restrictions, like
that on the precision of lat/lon coordinates. They will be chopped down
to the precision actually used by the FG implementation during the
conversion process. IMO, the proposed precision of 1 meter is totally
unacceptable. It would even not allow to display the aircraft correctly.
Also, intermediate points at lines, polygons etc. require a much greater
precision than that of geographic data used.


Another important function of converters would be resolving scenery
conflicts. While some FG versions may be clever enough to do this
automatically, we cannot rely on this. Also, it may be better for
performance reasons to resolve scenery conflicts at the conversion time.
Scenery conflicts will have to be resolved during the conversion from
the mid-level into the low-level format, because scenery design tools do
not understand scenery file formats from other tools.

Resolving scenery conflicts could be done in a variety of ways - by
deleting duplicate objects, terrain and navaids from other sceneries, by
including some information about 'exclusion zones', or maybe doing
nothing, assuming the implementation of FGFS is clever enough to resolve
conflicts at run-time.


Converters from high-level into mid-level format should be portable
across all FG platforms. This should not be a big problem, because such
converters would normally not use any hardware/OS-specific functions.
This also means their source code must be publicly available. 


While all these conversions seem to be too complicated to be done by 
ordinary users, they can be automated. FG could automatically determine,
which converters are available and execute them without any interaction
with the user. Also, the user could 'customize' FGFS by determining
different ways of conversion.

Pre-processing scenery data before using the scenery would make FGFS
less flexible in terms of scenery management than, say, MSFS. In the
worst case, the whole scenery database would have to be re-generated
each time a scenery package is installed or remove. However, I think the
achieved compatibility of scenery data would justify this price.


Distributing scenery files in a high-level format would create
additional non-technical problems. For example, some scenery designers
may feel uncomfortable about releasing what basically is their source
code. Maybe some mechanisms could be introduced to prevent 'stealing' of
the scenery, but IMO it is not the top priority now.


We can learn a lot from errors we (and not Microsoft, BTW) made with
MSFS. 

Almost all MSFS sceneries are distributed in the lowest-level format -
as BGL files. When a small bug (I think it was something with magvar) in
the Airport program was discovered, scenery authors had to recompile all
sceneries and upload new versions in order to get it fixed. For this
reasons, lots of scenery files still contain this bug.

Had the authors uploaded their Airport source files instead of BGL files
and tell the users to convert them into BGLs, the problem would become
non-existent as soon as a new (bug-fixed) converter would be uploaded.

When FS5.1 was introduced, lots of problems appeared because of synth
mountain heights. Had scenery authors uploaded their source files, all
synth mountains IN ALREADY RELEASED SCENERIES could be fixed simply by
releasing updated versions of scenery compilers.

This shows how important it is to distribute sceneries in the
highest-possible-level format.

Also, many problems were caused by a changed elevation of the ground
scenery. It would be very easy to write a converter that would adjust
heights of runways etc. to match the new world scenery - it would not
even require the source code for the scenery. However, no one bothered
to do that. Thousands of man-hours were put into manually fixing the
sceneries for FS5.1 instead. Had this effort been spent onto designing
new areas or enhancing existing sceneries (as opposed to fixing), we
would have much more good scenery for MSFS now!

These are only a few examples out of many.

IMO, we created most compatibility problems between FS5.0 and 5.1
ourselves, and now the same thing will probably happen between FS5.1 and
FSFW95. Microsoft programmers simply did their job - enhancing MSFS.
Enhancing _any_ software product creates compatibility problems, so we
shouldn't blame Microsoft for them. We could easily avoid most of the
problems if we would have looked a bit more into the future.

It is very important not to repeat the same errors in FGFS.


A good starting point in FGFS scenery design could be (even if this
sounds strange) developing a converter into the BGL file format used by
MSFS and developing some high-level scenery design tools. This would
allow designing sceneries that could already be used with MSFS, but
would be compatible with FGFS or other flight simulators, should
converters for them exist. Should some implementation of FGFS become a
reality, it would probably be a good idea to develop a converter _from_
BGL files into the mid-level format used by FGFS. This would allow using
(most of) existing MSFS sceneries without having to re-design them from
scratch again. Of course, these sceneries would not be as good as
high-level sceneries specially developed for FGFS, because they would
not enhance themselves with new versions of FG. But they would build a
solid scenery base for the beginning.


Maybe a similar approach could also be made to other components of FG,
such as aircraft, panels etc.

Any opinions?
-- 
