Konstantin Kukushkin <kukushk@itereu.de> wrote:
> > In the discussions about bits and bytes we should not forget one of the
> > most important features of FGFS (maybe the most important one) -
> > compatibility.
> > 
> > The compatibility of scenery data is needed between different platforms,
> > between different versions of FG (upwards/downwards) and between
> > sceneries produced by different scenery design tools. By different
> > platforms I also mean different FG implementations for one hardware
> > platform. 


Dean Catalano replied:
> Just an idea that popped into my head, would it be best to have a common
> scenery scripting language that could be interpreted by scenery compilers
> for each platform that FGFS runs on. These source codes could become the
> distributable versions.
> 
> This is a very abstract idea, but I'm a novice when it comes to scenery
> design. Just food for thought.


Dean,

I would tend to agree with you.  We should come up with a scenery
scripting language.  Depending on how we design things, it could/might
look remarkably like one of the existing FS5 scenery compiler
languages.

I think it would be a very good thing for Flight Gear if we could take
advantage of all the existing FS5 scenery.  One way to do this (*if we
had the authors permission*) would be to run the scenery through a
.bgl de-compiler, and then recompile it into Flight Gear scenery.
This would allow us to get around the machine dependencies of the .bgl
format.

Finally, I believe all Flight Gear scenery should be distributed (or
at least available) in "source code" form.  Again this would allow us
to "compile" it for any platform.  It would be a little contrary to
the DOS world's way of releasing binaries only and protecting the
source, but it would fit right in with the Unix/Gnu philosophy of
making the code available.  After all, we are making the source code
to Flight Gear itself freely available.  One advantage to doing this
is that others can come along and improve the scenery for an area if
they like.  In the same way, others can come along and improve the
actual flight gear code if they like.

[oops, I'm going to get a little political here.]

I believe this open nature is at the heart of what will make Flight Gear
successful.  Because anyone has access to the code, we can draw on the
talents, skills, and abilities of people all over the world.  If we
restrict access to the code we only limit our potential.  This is why
commercial flight simulators (while very good) will eventually come in
second place to Flight Gear.  

Time will tell.

Well, off to go play some more "Pick-up Sticks" with the latest Flight
Gear code. :-)

Curt.
