Justin Tyme writes:
> How about setting up a non-profit corporation which, among other
> things, would cover the manufacturing, packaging, and distribution
> costs, plus offer grants to designers of planes, panels, scenery, etc.
> to cover the costs of their creativity?  At least this would give us
> control and legitimacy.  A portion of the proceeds could be donated to
> appropriate charities.  I think the Flight Gear project could be
> incorporated (no pun intended) very easily into such an organization.
> We could defray the start up costs by a $10 charter lifetime
> membership fee.  When Flight Gear is ready we could already have the
> distribution channels in place for mass-distribution . . . .
> 
> How 'bout "The Right Brothers Foundation"?  (hope that not sexist)

How 'bout FSFW Foundation?  (Flight Simulator Free Ware)

> Somebody take this and run with it . . .

Justin,

This sounds like a good idea.  I'm not sure how it could be fairly and
practically implemented, but I do like the idea and I think it is
worth looking into in greater depth.

You mention Flight Gear which is why your message caught my eye,
however if something like this were to be set up, I believe it should
encompass all free [civilian?] flight-sim developers who wish to
participate and should *not* be limited to a specific program or
platform.

I was going to write a couple more paragraphs here, but I realize that
I would just be echoing what you said above, so I will just summarize:

    1.  This will provide those stinkin' thieves with a little honest
        competition.
    2.  It will help to bring your "product" to more users.
    3.  It will help cover/defer/make bearable the costs of the
        developers efforts.
    4.  Will help encourage and speed development of cool new stuff.

I have been thinking along related topics in the context of the Flight
Gear project.  There would be several challanges to address:

    1.  How would the money be divided up in a fair way between such a
        wide variety of developers?

        My lovely wife had the following suggestion.  Create a couple
        of categories of developers (such as 3).  If you designed
        scenery for many countries, or created a whole fleet of aircraft from
        scratch, you would most likely end up in the top category.  If
        you designed scenery for a medium size area, or just do a lot
        of quality Microsoft bashing you would end up in the middle
        category.  If you just did scenery for some small airport, or
        repainted the 747, you might end up in the bottom category.
        We could split 50% of the proceeds among the top
        developers, 35% among the middle level developers, and 15%
        among the bottom level developers.

        Of course we would have to clearly define the rules for
        assigning people to categories.  We would also have to discuss
        the proper percentage breakdown for the different classes of
        developers. 

    2.  Would it be realistic to see our cd show up in the local
        comp-usa any time soon?

    3.  There are a number of good mail order cd-rom places that
        specialize in distributing freeware.  It might be possible to
        hook up with something like that to take advantage of their
        distribution channels.

    4.  Most of the 3rd party development has been given away for
        free.  This scheme works well many nice dynamics.  Will
        injecting money in the equation spoil things for
        everyone.  I think the developers should realize that they
        won't get rich from this anyways, and still maintain a 
        "for free" attitude.

    5.  I believe, that even if our products are placed on our CD, we
        should still continue to make everything freely downloadable
        as it currently is.

        I don't think we should include any shareware, or commercial
        demos.  If we do include shareware, the shareware authors
        should probably not be included in the money disbursement.

We should also accept donations.  I can think of several ways in which
a project like Flight Gear (http://www.menet.umn.edu/~clolson/fgfs)
could benifit commercial aviation companies.

For instance, lets say I am the manufacturer of some really cool new
GPS with tons of bells and whistles.  If this new instrument was
modelled in Flight Gear, then I (the company) could send a copy of
Flight Gear on cd along with a nice color brochure and video tape to
prospective customers.  The customer could then pop the cd into his
computer and take the the GPS gizmo on a test drive from his favorite
airport in his favorite plane.

Or, maybe I'm trying to sell kits for a homebuilt aircraft ... this
would be a great try before you buy marketing tool.  Try out the plane
in simulation and see how it performs.  So after 100 tries, you
finally landed the simulator without crashing ... you are all set to
hop in the real thing and go for it ... :-) ... just kidding.

Since flight gear will have an open multi-platform architecture and
source code will be available, it should be fairly straightforward for
a company to model whatever they are trying to sell.

How much would something like this be worth to a company?  Would it
significantly help sales?  I think it could for many products.  If a
company were allowed to ship out CD's of flight-gear (and other flight
sim tools scenery, panels, aircraft, sounds, etc.), they could
negotiate a nice contribution to our non-profit organization.


The more I think about it, the more I feel that this is a great idea
who's time is long over due.  Why not officially join forces for the
benifit of everyone?  All you people out there who are taking
advantage of tons of free scenery, planes, add on utilities, etc.,
wouldn't it be worth it to have them all on one cd in one spot so you
don't have to waste hours and hours finding and downloading them?

Ok, this message is long enough for now.  Now all we need is somebody
who knows something about setting up non-profit organizations, and
some developers to sign on!  Count me in, I could handle $10, I just
won't buy my dog a rawhide bone this week.

Later,

Curt.
