I have the urge to write some sort of summary/status report so here we
go.


1. Eric's efforts.  

Eric has been doing a wonderful job of creating the building blocks
for Flight Gear.  He has been crafting all the low level routines that
will form the foundation of Flight Gear.  He has been hard at work and
many of the pieces are starting to fit together.  Have a look at the
initial code at his web site if you haven't already:

    http://www.cea.berkeley.edu/~korpela/html/

We owe you a few beers. :-)


2. The Flight Gear Web page

I have done a little work this weekend updating the content of the FG
web page (http://www.menet.umn.edu/~clolson/fgfs/).  Specifically I
have created a sub-page that lists what I know about the status of the
various sections of this project.  I encourage everyone to have a look
at the FG web page and let me know if you have any updates or
corrections to make.

If you see yourself fitting into any of the various sub projects, let
me know and I can add your name to the appropriate spots.


3. Non-profit Organization

There has been some discussion on the Flight-Sim@grove.iup.edu mailing
list about possibly setting up a non-profit organization.  Any
freeware flight-sim developers would be welcomed to join the
organization.  They would create cdrom collections of the various free
ware flight sim products created by the member developers.  The
motiviations for doing this are:

    - Help combat the growing trend of people stealing and selling the
      developers hard work.

    - Provide an increased market and larger distrubution for these
      products.

    - Provide a small income in the form of grants to help defer the
      developer's costs of purchasing resources.

    - Promote and encourage additional freeware development.

Note:  All the products on the cdrom would still be available for free
downloading from the internet as before.

It seems that if this organization is created, it might make sense for
us to join.  People are just talking right now, but it is something
that might be worthwhile paying attention to.


4. Future Flight Gear Road Map

Eric's work has been coming along very nicely.  He has written several
simple demo modules to test and demonstrate his code.  All those who
are serious about contributing the the Flight Gear effort might want
to start looking at the code and the example modules.  I think we are
to the point where we might be able to begin working on some of the
other sections of code in parallel.

For example (and these are just random things off the top of my head)
people could start looking at:

    - Finding/recording various engine sounds and other sound effects
    - Building flight model(s).
    - etc.

It might be too early to really start cranking on the various pieces,
but I think we are to the point where we could start looking into some
of these things.


Well, my dog is insisting that I take him for a run, so that's all for
now. 

Curt.
