I had some thoughts on this which I expressed in a posting some time
ago. My idea was to make scenery development as platform- independent as
possible, and to allow chaotic development of scenery design tools. For
example, it would be possible to use FS5 sceneries with FGFS and FGFS
sceneries with FS5. This would require some conversion tools, but any
thinking about these can only start after programmers agree on the
low-level format. IMHO, the proposed ODL is too abstract to be the
low-level format. However, a worked-out version of it could serve as a
common denominator for graphical object design utilities.

> I'm not sure how far along we are, but if we are going to have
> different teams that work alongside the kernel developers (like
> Eric), shouldn't there be a team whose job it is to come up
> with the structure of all the binaries and of the scripting
> language used to build and compile scenery, aircraft, and the
> like?

I am not planning to join the FGFS development team now, but I will
probably consider FGFS in my scenery design tools. That is, I will leave
a 'back door' which will allow writing a converter into FGFS in the
future.

> * A CAD-like program for building aircraft

I am planning to start some work on a 3-D object designer for FS5/FS95
in the near future. I could make it capable of producing some output
that could be used in the Flight Gear project too. Then, my tool could
be useful for FS95 _and_ FGFS at the same time.

> * GUI-based compilers for scenery

Again, I think it is now pointless to write a big scenery design utility
specially for FGFS. It is still too hypothetical now, and this means too
little motivation for developing dedicated freeware (and commercial too)
tools. However, it would be possible to leave 'back doors' in scenery
design utilities for, say, FS95, that would allow using them to design
FGFS scenery when the time comes.

Regards
