 Personally I don't see how any fair distribution of any money could ever be
worked out and too much time would be spent trying to figure that out rather
than working on code.

 People just have to decide if they want to be a part of this project or not.
 If they want to do another project that is money driven even if it is to cover
expenses then that's a whole different thing. This should be a hobby and that
means people who do the hobby pay their own costs.

 Secondly combating theivery of peoples work can't be a big goal either. Either
something is going to be free and the code in the public domain or it's not. It
too hard to do it any other way. People who contribute code need to do it
knowing there is a good chance that if it becomes popular part of it will be
explioted by commercial people. That is the sign of success. I think that
allowing both commercial and non commercial exploitation of the code
encourages quick adoption and widespread desemination. After something is up
and running that is good enough to make people want to use it  then there will
be plenty of opportunity for developers to make money to offset costs by 
creating commercial add ons if they feel the need to do that. But they better
be good if they are going to compete with the freeware stuff that will come
out. One only has to look at the abundance of free scenery for FS5 out there
to realize that.

 If people secretly desire to get some money from this project (they may not
even realize this themselves yet) and are going to feel jilted later if it
doesn't happen then they are getting involved in the wrong project.

 I can say that this thread alone has probably discouraged several people from
wanting to get involved.

 Instead people should be discussing texture mapping, multiplayer connections
(internet please not just ipx), combat and general aviation issues, flight
modeling techniques, collision detection, sound effects, scalability of all of
the above for slower and faster machines etc.

 The code hould have a central data structure where exchange of realevant
conditions are exchanged between program threads or modules.
 Ideally the amount of processors time allocated to each module could be
proportioned dynamically by the user. thu those who care more about visuals
could set the terrain renederer to get 70 percent of the CPU loops and those
who care more about flight modeling could set that module to get more of the
CPU loops.
 The default would be for the program to cycle through each loop spending as
much time as defined in each one.

 Thus say in the main data exchange structure the planes current position,
speed, and rates of change of position etc would be in a data structure that
could be accessed by the terrain rendering module, the flight module, the
weather module, the collision module, the internet multiplayer module, etc
etc. If this data structure is defined it becomes easy for others to
independently develop modules without being involved in all parts of the code.
Ideally each module would be a separate dll file so one could simply chose the
dll file they want on their sytem to change the modules. Thus maybe one
wireframe terreainrenderer would be available and maybe another would be
texture mapped or 3D. Which is wanted by the end user could be copied to his
hard drive.

 Maybe a list of generic dll names to be called by the main loop would be:
 terrain.dll
 collision.dll
 flighteq.dll
 internet.dll
 sounds.dll

 Thus people could just rename the terrain rendering dll of their choice
terrain.dll and the program would use it.
 Obviously each dll module would need to provide common functions and
procedutres but how they did each function could be different.

 So lets say the main data exchange structure holds the current position and
velocity and angular vectors for the plane. Johnny can now write a terrain
render module based on reading that structure alone, David can write a flight
module using that and airframe info and, Billy can write a collision module
for combat or crashes. Every one can concentrate on what they like and
multiple mudules can be available for download so the program can be very
customized just by which module you decide to download.

 On texture mapping I have a few thoughts:
 The rendering model should provide for different ground textures to be used at
different heights above the earth. This would avoid the tiling effect one gets
in FS when high above the ground.

 Another good idea would be for it to display angled textures such as a texture
for when the craft is looking toward or away from the ground. Thus a front view
would show texture "woodsfront" and a look straight down would show "woods
down" and a look out the back would show "woodsretreat" textures.
 This would provide a means to have a real sense of traveling over the ground.
a forest or anyother thing looks different whether you are looking at it as
you approach or on top of it or have passed it and are looking out the rear
view window.

 I propose a layered standard texture name system for all textures.
 for example wdsfxx.txr where xx is a number.
 Thus wdsfxx would be woods textures as seen approaching from the front
windscreen with a number designating it's detail level.

 Everyone would have a basic wdsf01 texture on their system along with plains,
farms, ice, water, etc. Scenery designers could specify a wdsf34 texture in
their scenery files. The program would know to look for the wdsf34 texture but
if it wasn't found the program would default to the next level of genericness
(indicated by a lower number) using the wdsf01 in the end for example if no
other texture was available.
 The beauty of this system is it would allow the use of huge highly detailed
texture maps for those who wanted to download them yet would allow those who
don't to still enjoy the scenery with the generic levels of textures.

 Those are some thoughts for now.


Regards,

George Watson  Warbirds "HOLO"

